'''Level 825''', known informally as '''Van Zant''', is the 826<sup>th</sup> level of the backrooms.

==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=RowTanks.png|caption=A photo of a stairwell branching off of a floor.}}The level opens into a small lobby. It is quiet and evenly lit, with no obvious indication of its position within the structure. From this space, stairwells branch away in multiple directions. Each one appears identical at a glance. After moving through several of them, it becomes difficult to tell whether a stairwell has already been traversed.


Wanderers entering Level 825 typically arrive near what would be considered the eight hundredth floor. There is nothing in the environment to confirm this number. No signage or numbering exists. The estimate is based on reports and tracking attempts. From this point onward, the stairwells continue upward and downward without visible change.

Every five flights of stairs, the stairwell opens onto a floor. These floors are small, often no larger than a modest hallway junction or waiting area. Most measure only a few meters across, have low ceilings, and offer limited walking space. They are enclosed on all sides, offering no sense of openness or relief. The floors are tiled with square stone slabs arranged in a tight grid. Muted greens, browns, and dark reds repeat across the surface in no apparent pattern. The tiles are heavily worn, and scuff marks overlap in places. Some tiles feel slightly uneven underfoot, smoothed down rather than damaged. None appear cracked or loose.

Walls throughout the level are coated in textured paint. The colors sit somewhere between faded peach and beige, dulled by age and constant light. A low wainscoting panel runs along the base of each wall, painted a lighter tone and kept surprisingly clean. Corners and seams show minor wear, but nothing appears broken.

The ceiling is a standard drop ceiling that spans every floor. Rectangular fluorescent panels are arranged in a grid, casting a flat, white light that never flickers or dims. Vent grilles and access panels are spaced evenly among the lights. Some panels are locked shut. Others appear functional, though no airflow can be felt beneath them.

Furnishings are sparse. A few upholstered chairs sit against the walls on certain floors, their cushions slightly compressed. The fabric is plain and neutral, with faint discoloration along the edges. Large potted plants are placed near corners and doorways. Their leaves are full and healthy, and the soil appears undisturbed, despite no visible signs of watering or care.

Spending extended time on these floors gives little sense of progress. The chairs remain where they are, no matter how often they are used. The plants neither grow nor wilt. The lighting remains unchanged. Without clocks, windows, or variations in sound, estimating the passage of time becomes difficult. Some floors contain narrow windows set directly into the walls. Their placement feels inconsistent. These windows do not reveal other rooms or exterior spaces. Behind the glass is only darkness. No reflection returns from it, and no depth can be judged. Light from the surrounding area seems to vanish at the surface. Most wanderers avoid standing near these windows for long.

Prolonged traversal of the stairwells places a gradual mental strain on wanderers. Eventually, counting floors becomes unreliable. Brief lapses in attention are enough to erase any sense of direction or progress. Some wanderers report feeling as if they pass the same floor multiple times, though whether this is a fault of memory or of the structure remains unclear.{{Blurimage|file=RowTanks7.png|caption=A photo of a hallway captured by a wanderer.|bg-align=2|top=2}}


<div style=" background: #272727; color: white; padding:5px; border-left:10px solid #36373c; margin: 5px 0 5px 2px; box-shadow: 0px 0px 7px #000000;">
== ''Level 825 — Recovered Document'' ==

I entered through a small lobby. It was quiet and evenly lit, with no signs or windows to indicate where I was. My footsteps didn’t carry very far. Stairwells branched off in every direction. After a few flights, I couldn’t tell which ones I had already taken.

Most wanderers start around what some call the eight hundredth floor. There’s no way to know for sure. I’ve counted flights, but numbers blur after a while. Up and down, up and down. It’s endless.

Every so often, the stairwell opens into a small floor. Usually just a few meters across. Low ceilings, walls on every side. The floors are tiled in squares of faded green, brown, and red. The stones are worn smooth underfoot. Some tiles are uneven, but none are broken. Walls are painted in dull peach-beige, with lighter panels at the bottom. Everything looks cared for. Almost normal.

I had to reread the last paragraph. I don’t remember writing it.

A few chairs sit against the walls. I tried one. As I sat down, the cushion seemed to sigh, almost like it had a life of its own. It stayed that way no matter how long I sat. There are large potted plants in the corners. Their leaves are full and healthy, yet they remain eerily still. They never seem to move. I can't tell if they move or grow.

Time is hard to measure here. The lights never change, and the chairs never move. I can’t tell how long I’ve been on a floor before moving on. Some floors have narrow windows. I looked through one and saw nothing. No reflection, no depth. Just darkness. Standing too long near them made me uneasy. 

The stairwells are worse. Counting flights becomes impossible. My mind strains, lapses in attention are enough to make me forget where I’ve been. I’ve felt like I passed the same floor twice, maybe three times. A faint smell, like cleaning products, drifts through the stairwells. I can’t tell if I’ve noticed it before, or if I’m remembering it wrong. Sometimes, a distant, echoing cough disrupts the silence, adding to the confusion of whether these experiences are real or mere tricks of the level.

Every step I take is the same as the last, yet different. I keep moving because I have to, but I don’t know if I’m going up or down. The level stretches on, and I wonder if I will ever see the bottom—or the top.
</div>

==Entrances & Exits==
===Entrances===

* Wanderers traveling on [[Level 870]], may find that exiting a car during an abrupt stop places them at the top of a stairwell leading into Level 825.
* In [[Level 810]], moving too far into its corridors without interacting with door thresholds can pull a wanderer into a stairwell transition into Level 825.

===Exits===

* Past every 100-200 flights of stairs, you'll find a floor with a chance of having an unlocked door. If you go through an unlocked door, then you go to a random level
* If you make it to the bottom of the stairs section, then there will be a lobby. Going through the door in the lobby will automatically bring you to a '''safe''' level.


